We have recommended: 

That the Sangguniang Bayan pass a resolution properly authorizing the Municipal Mayor and Municipal Treasurer to open a separate bank account for the 20% Development fund. Furthermore the municipality should maintain a special account for the 20% Development fund as well as establish and maintain a complete set of subsidiary ledgers;
That management identify priority projects to be funded under the 20% development fund with sufficient details and particulars. Guidelines and policies involving the implementation of these programs or projects should be considered and included in the planning and budgeting stage;
That management submit the Program of Works as supporting documents to the Annual Investment Plan to aid in the further analysis of funded projects vis-a-vis actual expenditures. For lump sum appropriation, authorization from the Sangguniang Bayan should be obtained before implementation;
That management implement only projects set forth in the Annual Investment Program. In instances where other priority projects are identified for implementation, a Sangguniang Bayan resolution should first be passed for the realignment and revision of the Annual Investment Plan to be submitted for approval by the Sangguniang Panlalawigan; and
That management strictly comply with the provisions of DILG and DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2011-1 in the preparation and utilization of the 20% Development Fund to attain the desired socio-economic and environmental outcomes.

In view of the above noted deficiencies, we have recommended that:
The Sanggunian Bayan pass a resolution properly authorizing the Municipal Mayor and the Municipal Treasurer to open a separate bank account for the 20% Development Fund. Furthermore, maintain a special account for the fund as well as establish and maintain a complete set of subsidiary ledgers;
The management identify priority projects to be funded under the 20% Development Fund with sufficient details and particulars. Guidelines and policies involving the implementation of these programs or projects should be considered and included in the planning and budgeting stage;
The management submit the Program of Works as supporting documents to the Annual Investment Plan to aid in the further analysis of funded projects vis-à-vis actual expenditures. For lump sum appropriation, obtain authorization from the Sanggunian Bayan before implementation;
The management implement only projects set forth in the Annual Investment Program. In instances where other priority projects are identified for implementation, ensure proper realignment and revision of the AIP to be submitted for approval by the proper Sanggunian; and
The management strictly comply with the provisions of DILG and DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2011-1 in the preparation and utilization of the 20% DF to attain the desired socio-economic and environmental outcomes.

In view of the foregoing observations, we have recommended that management:
Justify the noted lapses and henceforth, familiarize themselves with the relevant provisions with regard to the utilization of the LDRRM funds;
Push for the enactment of a local ordinance creating the DRRM Office including the required staffing/personnel. Upon enactment, consider the immediate hiring of qualified DRRM Officer and staff;
Submit the bidding and other essential documents to support validity of transaction;
See to it that the unexpended/unobligated funds from prior years LDRRM are treated as Trust Liability at the end of the year and duly transferred to a special trust fund account to avoid misuse of funds; and
Utilize the LDRRMF for the acquisition of disaster preparedness equipment as well as immediate assistance and services to calamity stricken constituents.

